{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17634317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17634317"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:58:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:58:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17509"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17509"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.11,0.82,0.07,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10199"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77674"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10199"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17509"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63187"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10062"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23868"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23877"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77674"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAcetyl CoA is a key molecule in cellular metabolism that serves as the entry point for the citric acid cycle.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary pathway for acetyl CoA formation in well-nourished cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Deamination of amino acids","Beta-oxidation of fatty acids","Oxidative decarboxylation of pyruvate","Breakdown of ketone bodies","Reverse reaction of citrate synthase"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary pathway for acetyl CoA formation in well-nourished cells is through \u003Cstrong\u003Eoxidative decarboxylation of pyruvate\u003C/strong\u003E. This reaction occurs in the mitochondrial matrix and is catalysed by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex, which converts pyruvate derived from glucose into acetyl CoA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other pathways are alternative sources of acetyl CoA but are not the primary route in well-nourished cells:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-oxidation of fatty acids\u003C/strong\u003E becomes more important during fasting or prolonged exercise\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreakdown of ketone bodies\u003C/strong\u003E is significant only during periods of glucose shortage\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeamination of amino acids\u003C/strong\u003E contributes minimally to acetyl CoA formation under normal conditions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReverse reaction of citrate synthase\u003C/strong\u003E is not physiologically significant for acetyl CoA production\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pyruvate dehydrogenase complex requires five coenzymes: thiamine pyrophosphate, lipoic acid, coenzyme A, flavin adenine dinucleotide, and nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acetyl CoA is primarily formed from pyruvate via pyruvate dehydrogenase complex in the mitochondrial matrix.","Fatty acids and ketogenic amino acids can also be converted to acetyl CoA through beta-oxidation and various metabolic pathways.","Acetyl CoA is a crucial metabolic intermediate that feeds into the citric acid cycle for energy production."],"references":["Boron W. F., Boulpaep E. L. Medical Physiology. (3rd edition). US. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017.","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63187"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17509"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63187"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T21:32:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T00:05:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10199"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77674"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:24+10:30"},"relationships